rComments: I took Andrew Forward's class back in 2019, before Covid, so I can't say how he manages online school, but he was an immensely educational prof. His classes were challenging, sure, but he was more tuned in to the going ons of tech more than any other prof I've had. He gave insight into the industry when other profs stuck purely to theory in vacuum.

After having prof Andrew a few times I believe the rating isn't accurate. He can be unorganized (however has been improving) and the course load is heavy but he is fair and makes his best effort. He tends to incorporate group work for all his courses so make sure to pick a good group. He isn't a strict marker and can be lenient in that regard.

I really enjoyed this professor's class. I honestly do not know why he got so many negative reviews for SEG3103, but my guess is they were reviewing the course more so not the professor. I'll be real almost all SEG3000-4000 level is boring and dry. This professor was caring by prepping us for the exam and assignments through his weekly sync lecture

55% of the course (weight-wise) was group work, if you don't get a good group you're screwed. Group project + weekly group labs + group assignments are constant and hefty. Andrew is super disorganized despite teaching this course multiple times, and gives extremely inconsistent feedback. Super easy material, but he delivered it in the worst way.

Pretty chill guy but his recorded lectures are basically text-to-speech of slides and he can't offer further examples/clarification that isn't contradictory. He made the simplest concepts really confusing. Not to mention the lack of co-ordination between him and his TAs on what they expect from students regarding projects.

He is unqualified to teach SEG 3101 as his super messy material and unorganized teaching support. His lecture notes are like abstract paintings make you loss of judgement for key points. His video records are even more clownish, as if he was a rapper who flaunts his talking speed. He just kept slipping over or talk fast especially on key points.

I liked Prof. Forward. His style is different from most profs, he's less structured in his teaching , however you will learn a lot with him. He wants to expose you to as many real-world software engineering concepts as possible. He integrated Elixir in Summer 2021's curriculum so that was cool. He's approachable, down to earth, and easy marker.

Oh man, this guy is Aziz 2.0. Hes so bad. On the midterm he said it would need 1.5 hrs and he gave two extra hours. But in reality the midterm takes 3.5 hours. Also, he always says youre submissions need to stand on their own (they need to be clear). I wish if he follows what he says for his tests and assignments, sometimes its just pure blabber

Gave 2 hours extra for the midterm to "help you submit properly." He said it would only take an hour and a half to complete and the rest was for submissions. In reality the midterm took me 3 hours to complete. If u ask for any help or clarification on the midterm he will respond with a default "state your assumption and continue."

Prof Forward's lectures, at least for SEG 3103, are very abstract (high-level) and don't provide the technical knowledge needed to complete homework and labs. He responds to emails quickly though, which is nice.
Would not take again.

The prof is a mess. He cant do anything literally the seat he sits has more benefits to the class than him. Man goes through the entire lecture thinking hes in a rap battle and reads off of the slides. Please also note that he reads from a different slideshow than the one he presents and he gives you both of the slides just to confuse you more.

Doesn't prepare you for assignments properly. Gave us an assignment that uses elixir, a language no one knows or uses. Why not just use java to test our knowledge on the material learnt in class. His lectures were very condensed and hard to follow. Lab aren't very understandable as the slides have little to no instructions in them.

Professor's lectures and lab sessions do not prepare you for the homework and tests. I would often be more confused after a lecture than before. The fact that 90% of the class voted that they were unprepared for the first homework assignment is less than surprising.

Mismanaged class. Nobody knows what to expect for exams. Very little material to learn from. Labs are so error prone and frustrating. I doubt most students are learning anything in this mess of a class. Avoid!

Such a horrible prof. He honestly tries his best not to teach. He records a 50 minute video to talk about a lecture intended for 3 hours. He basically improvises in his life lectures and you basically dont know what to expect. No clear schedule. The tutorials which are meant for concept clarification are much slower than the asynchronous lecture.

His communication of the material is poor. He frequently mispronounces words or confuses what he is trying to say, which can be hard to follow when you are watching a pre-recorded video and cannot clarify what he means in real time. I wish there was a textbook to self-study the course but have to rely entirely on his explanation. Wouldn't recommend

This professor is truly one of the best I've had. The lectures and material are clear, as well as the expectations. If you listen to class and do all the labs, the class is an easy A or A+. He is also easily accessible through Piazza and his emails (or in person). Although he is a part time professor, he is easily one of the best.

A great professor. He's lectures are clear and organized, where he would rewrite his lecture codes step by step from scratch, including debugging processes, which helps you to understand the basics of Java and OOP. However, I would say the course is NOT easy, especially for beginners. You have to have some self-learning spirit to get a high mark.

Went into great detail when doing lecture coding. Was really helpful for a beginner coder to understand why something is done in a specific way. Also was incredibly lenient with deadlines. Multiple extensions were given on assignments.

He is the G.O.A.T. Most caring professor I've ever had. His lectures are a little bit slow but at least you leave the lecture understanding stuff. He's good at explaining "why we should this way" or "why we might prefer doing the other way."

only lecture video, and submit assignment and labs are so wired you need to go one web first and upload by another website. and also there are so many rules to submit assignment and labs u have to read lots of things from his lab notes lecture video so short
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Lecture heavy', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: He's a great prof who's very clear with his explanations. It's easy to get marks with 5% for tutorial and 5% for lab attendance. Homeworks prepare you really well for the midterm and final (and those should be easy A's if you do the work). The final project is interesting and lets you really learn and apply a lot of new skills.
